b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe38313.htm)  [Next](sbe38315.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1417930330/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n_The Vedanta Sutras of Badarayana, Commentary by Sankara (SBE38)_ , tr. by\nGeorge Thibaut [1896] at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\n13\\. And because scripture declares that.\n\nThe text, 'Going upwards by that he reaches immortality,' declares that\nimmortality is reached by going. But immortality is possible only in the\nhighest Brahman, not in the effected one, because the latter is transitory. So\nscripture says, 'Where one sees something else, that is little, that is\nmortal' ( _Kh_. Up. VII, 24, 1). According to the text of the Ka _th_\na-upanishad also the going of the soul is towards the highest Brahman; for\nafter the highest Brahman has been introduced there as general subject-matter\n--in the passage, 'That which thou seest,' &c., I, 2, 14, no other kind of\nknowledge is taken up later on.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: IV, 3, 14](sbe38315.htm)\n\n"